04108nam a22005535i 9780822393696DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223936967 a10.1515/97808223936962doi  a(DE-B1597)553166  a(OCoLC)1125498943  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDT516.4 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a966.4041 aJackson, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLife Within Limits :bWell-being in a World of Want /cMichael Jackson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (245 p.) :b20 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tImagining Firawa -- tFathers and Sons -- tForty Days -- tScenes from a Marriage -- tSmoke and Mirrors -- tThings Hidden Since the Foundation of the World -- tThe Reopening of the Gate of Effort -- tSomething's Missing -- tThe Politics of Storytelling -- tThe Road to Kabala -- tTheir Eyes Were Watching God -- tAlbitaiya -- tThe Year of Supernatural Abundance -- tStrings Attached -- tThe Shape of the Inconstruable Question -- tNot to Find One's Way in a City -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe sense that well-being remains elusive, transitory, and unevenly distributed is felt by the rich as well as the poor, and in all societies. To explore this condition of existential dissatisfaction, the anthropologist Michael Jackson traveled to Sierra Leone, described in a recent UN report as the "least livable" country in the world. There he revisited the village where he did his first ethnographic fieldwork in 1969-70 and lived in 1979. Jackson writes that Africans have always faced forces from without that imperil their lives and livelihoods. Though these forces have assumed different forms at different times-slave raiding, warfare, epidemic illness, colonial domination, state interference, economic exploitation, and corrupt government-they are subject to the same mix of magical and practical reactions that affluent Westerners deploy against terrorist threats, illegal immigration, market collapse, and economic recession. Both the problem of well-being and the question of what makes life worthwhile are grounded in the mystery of existential discontent-the question as to why human beings, regardless of their external circumstances, are haunted by a sense of insufficiency and loss. While philosophers have often asked the most searching questions regarding the human condition, Jackson suggests that ethnographic method offers one of the most edifying ways of actually exploring those questions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aHappinesszSierra Leone. 0aPovertyzSierra Leone. 0aWell-beingzSierra Leone. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393696zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393696423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393696.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles